06380nam a22006855i 9780822379867DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223798677 a10.1515/97808223798672doi  a(DE-B1597)553308  a(OCoLC)893681277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aBUS0220002bisacsh00aEthnicity, Markets, and Migration in the Andes :bAt the Crossroads of History and Anthropology /cBrooke Larson, Enrique Tandeter, Olivia Harris. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b6 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tI Introduction -- tI. Andean Communities, Political Cultures, and Markets: The Changing Contours of a Field -- tII From Inca to Spanish Rule: The Making of Indians and Markets -- t2. Did Tribute and Markets Prevail in the Andes before the European Invasion? -- t3. The Variety and Ambiguity of Native Andean Intervention in European Colonial Markets -- t4. Exchange in the Ethnic Territories between 1530 and 1567: The Visitas of Huanuco and Chucuito -- t5. Exchange and Markets in the Sixteenth Century: A View from the North -- tIII Andean Tribute, Migration, and Trade: Remapping the Boundaries of Ethnicity and Exchange -- t6. Indian Migration and Social Change in Seventeenth-Century Charcas -- t7. Indians in Late Colonial Markets: Sources and Numbers -- t8. Markets, Power, and the Politics of Exchange in Tapacari, c. 1780 and 1980 -- tIV Negotiating the Meanings of Market Exchange: Community and Hierarchy in Three Andean Contexts -- t9. Ethnic Calendars and Market Interventions among the Ayllus of Lipes during the Nineteenth Century -- t10. The Sources and Meanings of Money: Beyond the Market Paradigm in an Ayllu of Northern Potosi -- t11. "Women Are More Indian": Ethnicity and Gender in a Community near Cuzco -- tV Conclusion -- t12. Ethnic Identity and Market Relations: Indians and Mestizos in the Andes -- tGlossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil now, Andean peasants have primarily been thought of by scholars as isolated subsistence farmers, "resistant" to money and to different markets in the region. Ethnicity, Markets, and Migration in the Andes overturns this widely held assumption and puts in its place a new perspective as it explores the dynamic between Andean cultural, social, and economic practices and the market forces of a colonial and postcolonial mercantile economy.Bringing together the work of outstanding scholars in Andean history, anthropology, and ethnohistory, these pioneering essays show how, from the very earliest period of Spanish rule, Andean peasants and their rulers embraced the new economic opportunities and challenged or subverted the new structures introduced by the colonial administration. They also convincingly explain why in the twentieth century the mistaken idea developed that Andean peasants were conservative and unable to participate effectively in different markets, and reveal how closely ethnic inequalities were tied to evolving market relations. Inviting a critical reconsideration of ethnic, class, and gender issues in the context of rural Andean markets, this book will revise the prevailing view of Andean history and provide a more fully informed picture of the complex mercantile activities of Andean peasants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic Conditions.2bisacsh1 aRuibal, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, Brooke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSempat Ass